## 4. Tenant & Organization Model\
\
### 4.1 What Is a Tenant?\
\
Every organization that signs up gets its own **tenant**. All data (aircraft, users, logbooks, documents) is scoped to that tenant's `org_id`.\
\
```\
org_01HABC (Horizon Flights LLC)\
  \uc0\u9500 \u9472 \u9472  Users: 12\
  \uc0\u9500 \u9472 \u9472  Aircraft: 8\
  \uc0\u9474    \u9500 \u9472 \u9472  N1234X \'97 Cessna 172\
  \uc0\u9474    \u9500 \u9472 \u9472  N5678Y \'97 Piper Archer\
  \uc0\u9474    \u9492 \u9472 \u9472  ...\
  \uc0\u9500 \u9472 \u9472  Logbooks: 47\
  \uc0\u9492 \u9472 \u9472  Documents: 204\
\
org_01HDEF (Mike's Aircraft Services)      \uc0\u8592  completely separate\
  \uc0\u9500 \u9472 \u9472  Users: 3\
  \uc0\u9500 \u9472 \u9472  Aircraft: 2\
  \uc0\u9492 \u9472 \u9472  ...\
```\
\
### 4.2 Cross-Organization Interactions (Aircraft Sharing)\
\
While organizations are isolated, the system supports **controlled cross-org linking** for aircraft sharing:\
\
- An **owner** in Org A can share an aircraft with a **mechanic** who has a standalone account (Org B or personal workspace)\
- This creates an `aircraft_access` record \'97 the mechanic sees the aircraft in their portal, but it still **belongs to Org A**\
- The owner in Org A can revoke this at any time\
\
